derivation.yuyuan_name: late 16th cent.: from Dutch cassier or French caissier, from caisse 'cash'
late 16th cent. (in the sense 'dismiss or disband troops'): from Flemish kasseren 'disband (troops') or 'revoke (a will'), from French casser 'revoke, dismiss', from Latin quassare (see quash)

entry.def: A cashier is a person who customers pay money to or get money from in places such as shops or banks.
If a person in the armed forces is cashiered, he or she is forced to leave because they have done something seriously wrong.

example.ex: The government had to recall many officers who had been cashiered on political grounds.

means.word_mean: 1. an employee of a bank who receives and pays out money
